In [RestTestsFromSnippetsTask](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/blob/master/build-tools-internal/src/main/groovy/org/elasticsearch/gradle/internal/doc/RestTestsFromSnippetsTask.groovy) , it looks like the intended behavior is to delete the folder testRoot/rest-api-spec/test , if it already exists, then recreate it and fill it in with the generated doc snippets.  It doesn't work.  If you put some garbage.txt file in that folder, run "gradle :docs:buildRestTest", then check the results, you find that garbage.txt is still sitting there.  There are two problems.

The contructor includes this, where "outputRoot()" returns the folder to be deleted, as a java.io.File object:

```groovy
doFirst { outputRoot().delete() }
```

The intuitive thing would be for this closure to execute before the executeTask method, with the TaskAction annotation, found in the super class [SnippetsTask](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/blob/master/build-tools-internal/src/main/groovy/org/elasticsearch/gradle/internal/doc/SnippetsTask.groovy) .  That's not what happens.  The executeTask method is called first.  Which means that snippets are being created before the attempted delete.  Related demonstration code below.

Since the delete is attempted after the snippets are created, one would expect the task to delete its own output.  This doesn't happen either, which brings us to the second problem.

We have a File object, pointing to a folder, and we call its delete method.  If the folder isn't empty, the delete fails.  It doesn't respond to failure by throwing an IOException, it just returns false.  We aren't checking the return value from delete(), so this goes unnoticed.


I was surprised by the result of calling doFirst() inside a Task constructor, so I wrote a bit of test code to convince myself the actual behavior was really happening.  Two files:

build.gradle
```gradle
task demoTask(type: SimpleTask)

tasks.named("demoTask").configure {
	doLast {
		println "In doLast block, declared in build.gradle"
	}
	doFirst {
		println "In doFirst block, declared in build.gradle"
	}
}
```
and buildSrc/src/main/java/SimpleTask.java
```java
import org.gradle.api.DefaultTask;
import org.gradle.api.tasks.TaskAction;
import org.gradle.api.model.ObjectFactory;

import javax.inject.Inject;


public class SimpleTask extends DefaultTask {

        @Inject
        public SimpleTask(ObjectFactory of) {
                System.out.println("In SimpleTask constructor");
                doFirst( (t) -> System.out.println("In doFirst lambda, added in the SimpleTask constructor") );
        }

        @TaskAction
        public void start() {
                System.out.println("In the start method, which has the TaskAction annotation");
        }
}
```

The resulting output:

$ gradle demoTask

**> Configure project :**
In SimpleTask constructor

**> Task :demoTask**
In doFirst block, declared in build.gradle
In the start method, which has the TaskAction annotation
In doFirst lambda, added in the SimpleTask constructor
In doLast block, declared in build.gradle

Currently it appears that using a wildcard (`*`) to delete datastreams will delete ALL the datastreams if the wildcard does not match anything. If the wildcard matches some datastreams, only those datastreams will be deleted.

Reproduce:

```
1. Create lifecycle policy
PUT _ilm/policy/my-lifecycle-policy
{
  "policy": {
    "phases": {
      "hot": {
        "actions": {
          "rollover": {
            "max_primary_shard_size": "50gb"
          }
        }
      },
      "warm": {
        "min_age": "30d",
        "actions": {
          "shrink": {
            "number_of_shards": 1
          },
          "forcemerge": {
            "max_num_segments": 1
          }
        }
      },
      "delete": {
        "min_age": "735d",
        "actions": {
          "delete": {}
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

2. Create index template
PUT _index_template/my-index-template
{
  "index_patterns": [
    "first-template-*",
    "second-template-*"
  ],
  "data_stream": {},
  "composed_of": [ ],
  "priority": 500,
  "_meta": {
    "description": "Template for my time series data",
    "my-custom-meta-field": "More arbitrary metadata"
  }
}

3. Create first-template-test
PUT first-template-test/_bulk
{ "create":{ } }
{ "@timestamp": "2099-05-06T16:21:15.000Z", "message": "192.0.2.42 - - [06/May/2099:16:21:15 +0000] \"GET /images/bg.jpg HTTP/1.0\" 200 24736" }
{ "create":{ } }
{ "@timestamp": "2099-05-06T16:25:42.000Z", "message": "192.0.2.255 - - [06/May/2099:16:25:42 +0000] \"GET /favicon.ico HTTP/1.0\" 200 3638" }

3. Create second-template-test
PUT second-template-test/_bulk
{ "create":{ } }
{ "@timestamp": "2099-05-06T16:21:15.000Z", "message": "192.0.2.42 - - [06/May/2099:16:21:15 +0000] \"GET /images/bg.jpg HTTP/1.0\" 200 24736" }
{ "create":{ } }
{ "@timestamp": "2099-05-06T16:25:42.000Z", "message": "192.0.2.255 - - [06/May/2099:16:25:42 +0000] \"GET /favicon.ico HTTP/1.0\" 200 3638" }

4. Check all data streams created

GET _data_stream/*

Both data streams returned

5. Delete

DELETE _data_stream/first-template*

6. Check `second-template-test` still exists

GET _data_stream/*

Should still return `second-template-test`.

7. Delete

DELETE _data_stream/first-template*

6. Notice `second-template-test` no longer exists

GET _data_stream/*

Should still return `second-template-test`, but returns an empty array.
```

If you repeat these steps without ever creating `first-template-test`, the first wildcard delete deletes the `second-template-test`.

In https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/pull/77597, we started tracking usage of the Searchable Snapshots feature. The usage is returned by the `GET _license/feature_usage` API like so:

```json
{
  "features" : [
    {
      "family" : null,
      "name" : "searchable-snapshots",
      "context" : null,
      "last_used" : "2021-10-01T18:52:53.996Z",
      "license_level" : "platinum"
    }
  ]
}
```

Notice the `license_level` field in the response. It is set to `platinum`. However, according to https://www.elastic.co/subscriptions, Searchable Snapshots is an Enterprise level feature.
